description:
Saw this Turkey Vulture getting a drink (see third photo) on my way back to town while driving through Brunswick Canyon...

The water here is actually considered unfit for human use ... (and wildlife too, used to work on this BLM district in a wildlife capacity) - as it drains from a contaminated reservoir from above, and for several decades, the water has worked it's way through the soil, down into the drainage, predominantly near the mouth of Sand Canyon... 
The creek used to only flow intermittently/seasonally and for short periods of time, due to snow melt and rain. Riparian vegetation along the drainage was historically supported by water flowing below the surface of the drainage, aided by Badger Spring about 3 miles up the canyon.

description: This plant had tiny, thick, salt-repelling leaves and tiny, pink, five-petaled flowers. These were much drier than the others in the fluctuating wetlands which were connected to the ocean tides. This plant was built for this fluctuating, dynamic Salt Marsh ecosystem.

The bird had frosty white feathers, a mostly black beak, and black legs. The base of the beak was bright yellow. It waded in the salty pond which was split from the sea by coastal development on the Salt Marshes.

This plant grew in sheer abundance on the mud flats, easily being the dominant species of that plant community. The stems were thick, and rounded, like strands of "pickles". These grew in the disturbed Salt Marsh.

This plant grew in sheer abundance on the mud flats, easily being the dominant species of that plant community. The stems were thick, and rounded, like strands of "pickles". These grew in the Salt Marsh, within those wet, salty growing conditions.

The plant had large, semi-woody stems and thin, long green leaves (some were shriveled). The "messy" flowers were a brownish-white in color. These grew with the goldenbushes in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The plant had spread out bright-green leaves, but the attention was on the single bloom. The flower attracted lone honeybees with its four large, bright orange petals. These were abundant in the Coastal Sage Scrub restoration.

The low shrub grew mainly upright, with many semiwoody stalks. The leaves were small, rounded, and bright green. The few flowers were yellow, and had small, tiny petals. It grew in the Coastal Sage Scrub.
The plant was a medium size shrub with light shaded branches, which grew very densely and packed. Their small, thick leaves were bright green. It grew in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The bird was a social, and chatty passerine. The tail and wings had white strips along the bottoms, and the rest of the body had various shades of black, brown, and gray. I caught the bird in cool, midair action above the flowering Coastal Sage Scrub.
The grass-like plant had very beautiful, scattered, abundant blooms, with the soft purple petals and fluffy, yellow pollen in the center. It grew near low-growing shrubs in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The shrub was thriving indeed, with fresh green leaves, fleshy stems, and large yellow flowers with brown seedheads. These grew abundantly within the Coastal Sage Scrub, with a 
close view of the Pacific.

The wading, beautiful egret was large and white. The legs were all black and the bill was orange. It was stalking the flowers as if they were fish! It seemed slightly out of place in this restored Coastal Sage Scrub.
This abundant bird was a small passerine, with blotched brown wings and body, and a reddish head. It flew down onto the floor of the Coastal Sage Scrub, down from the fence.

The large birds had soft, ruffled, light brown feathers which were noticed, and the black spots on the wings as well. They both clung onto the glass wall which overlooked the restored Coastal Sage Scrub.

The cactus was very branched out, and the thick stems weren't smooth. The density of spine cover on the stems wasn't very thick. It had magenta purple blooms.  It was a widespread species in the restored Coastal Sage Scrub.
This distant bird was a small passerine, with blotched brown wings and body, and a reddish head. Seeking protection, it perched in the cholla in the restored Coastal Sage Scrub.
The grass-like plant had very beautiful, scattered, abundant blooms, with the soft purple petals and fluffy, yellow pollen in the center. It grew in a clearing within the Coastal Sage Scrub.

This bird was a small passerine, with blotched brown wings and body, and a reddish head. It darted along the ground next to the moist forbs and the irrigation pipe, perhaps searching for a puddle. It landed in the Coastal Sage Scrub.
The dense plant had large, semi-woody stems and thin, long green leaves. The "messy" flowers were a brownish-white in color. These weren't too common in the restored Coastal Sage Scrub.
The hawk was a large individual with a brown head, light underwings and belly, and the characteristic  rusty-red tail. It soared over the houses, and swooped above the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The cactus was very spread out in terms of growth, creating large flats of rounded prickly pads. The large spines were gray and toothpick-like. The yellow blossoms present were very beautiful, with attractive interiors. These grew in the restored Coastal Sage Scrub.
The thriving shrub was summer-deciduous, with green leaves, fleshy stems, and abundant yellow flowers with brown seedheads. It grew in thick concentrations in the restored Coastal Sage Scrub.

The plants were annuals which had spread out bright-green leaves, but the attention was all on those beautiful blooms. Those flowers proudly showed off their four large, bright orange petals. These were abundant in the Coastal Sage Scrub restoration.

The succulent was very showy and scenic, awe-inspiring to us and some hikers nearby. It was large, very light blue-gray, and the fronds were wide. Two flowering stalks were also seen. It grew in the restored Coastal Sage Scrub.

description: This plant grew in sheer abundance on the mud flats, easily being the dominant species of that plant community. The stems were thick, and rounded, like strands of "pickles". These all grew in the Salt Marsh, mostly forming massive expanses of green islands in the Bolsa Chica wetlands.

This plant had tiny, thick, salt-repelling leaves and tiny, pink, five-petaled flowers. These grew in the flats right above the point where saltwater submerges plants during high tide, in this fluctuating, dynamic Salt Marsh ecosystem.

The plant had large, light green leaves, which reminded me of a yerba mansa. However, in this ecosystem the species is different. The plant wasn't blooming at the time, but dried flowering remains were nearby. It grew in the Salt Marsh.

The bird was distant, but the characteristics were still visible. The seabird was mostly black, with glossy feathers and a long neck. Below the eyes and beak a patch of orange/red feathers were easily visible, characteristic of this species. It waddled like a penguin across the mudflat in the Salt Marsh.

The lizard was relatively well camouflaged with the dry landscape. However, I saw the faint orange and black scales on the underside and saw the creature more clearly. These were attracted to the sun like moths to a lamppost at night. These were abundant in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The egret's feathers were long, fluffy, and darker in color than the more common egrets. The head was a rusty red in color, the wings were gray. It groomed itself on the platform floating on top of the Salt Marsh waters.
The creeping plant had light green, thick, ovular leaves. The few blooms present were deep purple/magenta. It grew on the sunny, sandy slope in the Coastal Sage Scrub outcrop.
The lizard was light in color and had many geometric patterns. This most likely was a juvenile. It skittered under the sunlight in the open Coastal Sage Scrub.

The main shell was multi-colored, and the arms had dark shades of purple and black. The pincers were proportionate to the body, unlike those fiddler, kelp, sheep, etc. crabs. It skittered across the submerged sediment in the Salt Marsh bay.

This time, the lizard was not camouflaged with the dry landscape. When I saw the faint orange, black, and yellow scales on the underside, I saw the creature more clearly. These were attracted to the sun like moths to a lamppost at night. These were abundant in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

These fish were very mobile, commonly leaping and splashing on the water in a spontaneous manner. The fins were gray and triangular. The bodies were slick and dark gray/blue. These swam in the Salt Marsh, in the deeper reaches of the bay.

The lizard was relatively well camouflaged with the dry landscape. However, I saw the faint orange, yellow, and black scales on the underside and that outlined the creature more clearly. These were abundant in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The sparrow had mostly light brown and white coloration, much like other sparrow species. However, the head had bright yellow striping near the eye, which distinguished this species from others. It perched on the slope above the Bolsa Chica wetlands, the Salt Marsh which it calls home.
The large rushes were thick, dense, and "spiny", like the name suggests. This stand was growing in a Salt Marsh, perhaps in a brackish location.

The wasp was very small, thin, and non-parasitic. The abdomen was bright orange with a darker tip. The small wings were narrow and long. It crawled around the buckwheat flowers in the Coastal Sage Scrub.

The shrub grew mainly upright, with many semiwoody stalks. Some of those stalks were dead, however most were filled with foliage. The leaves were small, rounded, and bright green. It grew in the disturbed Coastal Sage Scrub.

The wading egret had frosty white feathers, a mostly black beak, and black legs. The base of the beak was bright yellow. Using the beak, the egret was making ripples on the water, perhaps to attract unwary fish. It lived in the healthy Salt Marsh community.

This plant grew in sheer abundance on the mud flats, easily being the dominant species of that plant community. The stems were thick, and rounded, like strands of "pickles". This one grew in the Salt Marsh, on the edge of an algae-infested corner of the wetlands.
The gallant, beautiful egret was large and white. The legs were all black and the bill was orange. It waded in the emerging afternoon sun in the shallow waters of the Salt Marsh.

The flying egret captures an unprecedented beauty found in few creatures in these wetlands. It was large and white. The legs were all black and the bill was orange. The huge, white wings formed an image like an angel flying effortlessly over the Salt Marsh.
